Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"–":"Deceased","1260–1330":"1260–1330","–Female":"Deceased","1280–1354":"1280–1354","1306–1382":"1306–1382","1308–1361":"1308–1361","1308–1363":"1308–1363","1322–Female":"1322–Deceased","–1298":"–1298","before 1303":"before 1303","1363":"1363","1330":"1330","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","about 1308":"about 1308","1322":"1322","1354":"1354","1298":"1298","1308":"1308","1306":"1306","Stonor Park, Oxfordshire, England":"Stonor, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Stonor, Oxfordshire, England":"Stonor, Oxfordshire, England","England":"England","Oxford, England":"Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud FitzLewis was born as the daughter of Sir John FitzJohn III of Rippingale. She married John